Suppose we build an algebraic structure with the following axioms:
{{begin-axiom}}
{{axiom | n = 0
        | lc= Closure Axiom
        | q = \forall a, b \in G
        | m = a \circ b \in G
}}
{{axiom | n = 1
        | lc= Associativity Axiom
        | q = \forall a, b, c \in G
        | m = a \circ \paren {b \circ c} = \paren {a \circ b} \circ c
}}
{{axiom | n = 2
        | lc= Right Identity Axiom
        | q = \exists e \in G: \forall a \in G
        | m = a \circ e = a
}}
{{axiom | n = 3
        | lc= Left Inverse Axiom
        | q = \forall x \in G: \exists b \in G
        | m = b \circ a = e
}}
{{end-axiom}}
Then this does '''not''' (necessarily) define a group (although clearly a group fulfils those axioms).

